<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOXING ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
BLOCKER REACHES OUT, TAKES STARLING'S TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maurice Blocker, taking advantage of a five-inch height advantage and a 2 
1/2-inch margin in reach over Marlon Starling, won the World Boxing Council 
welterweight title on a majority decision Sunday at Reno. 
</P>
<P>
"Last time I went in to fight for the belt. This time I came to take the belt," 
Blocker said. 
</P>
<P>
Judges Miguel Donate of Puerto Rico and Lynn Carter of New Jersey scored the 
fight 115-113 for Blocker, and Judge Chuck Giampa of Las Vegas saw it even at 
114-114. The Associated Press scored it 115-113 for Blocker. 
</P>
<P>
Blocker, at 6-foot-1, towered over the 5-8 Starling, but didn't hesitate to 
fight the champion inside. 
</P>
<P>
Blocker's only loss in 32 professional bouts was a 1987 decision to Lloyd 
Honeyghan for the WBC version of the title. Starling beat Honeyghan for the 
title a year later, stopping him in nine rounds. 
</P>
<P>
An unintentional head butt opened a deep cut under Starling's left eyebrow in 
the seventh round. His corner slowed the flow of blood between the remaining 
rounds, but the cut bothered him. 
</P>
<P>
After a slow first round, the fighters started mixing it up in the second. 
Starling (45-6-1) won the middle rounds on most of the scorecards, but faded in 
the last three. There were no knockdowns. 
</P>
<P>
Blocker, of Washington, D.C., was the No. 1 WBC contender going into the fight. 
He received $79,000. Starling, of Hartford, Conn., got $164,000. 
</P>
<P>
Third-ranked heavyweight contender Razor Ruddock of Canada overwhelmed Kimmuel 
Odum of Gary, Ind., and knocked him out in the third round of a scheduled 
10-round bout at Atlantic City, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
Ruddock, 24-1-1 with 18 knockouts, floored Odum with a right uppercut and a 
left hook to the head with two seconds remaining in the round. 
</P>
<P>
Odum, 13-4 with 12 knockouts, couldn't handle Ruddock's continual pressure and 
scored only with short flurries that had little impact. 
</P>
<P>
Referee Rudy Battle deducted a point from Ruddock's score because he knocked 
down Odum with a left hook seconds after the bell ending the second round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
