<HEADLINE>
<P>
LINES DRAWN IN 'MISS SAIGON' DISPUTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It seems that in this latest affront to the Asian-American community (the 
attitude of "Miss Saigon's" producer), we are again ignoring the sexism 
inherent in the casting. 
</P>
<P>
From Charlie Chan to Kurosawa's upcoming film (which is one import from Japan 
we ought to ban), whenever the leading male role is an Asian character, time 
and time again it is played by a white actor while Asian females have 
opportunities to play not only leading roles as Asian characters, as in "Miss 
Saigon," but in mainstream parts (witness Joan Chen in television's "Twin 
Peaks"). 
</P>
<P>
Is this the same mentality that ensures that no Asian male can work as a news 
anchor in this town? 
</P>
<P>
I doubt that the feminists are keeping a tally on that score. 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD A. CHUNG 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
