<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Lanie Jones and Frank Messina 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MORE WATER: What a difference a year makes. This time last year, the volume of 
water in the main reservoir serving San Clemente dropped to its lowest in 
history -- 17.3 million gallons -- jolting city officials into enacting a 
series of rationing laws that are the toughest in Orange County. Now, thanks to 
restrictions on lawn watering, building and excessive-use penalties, along with 
voluntary conservation, the 48-million-gallon-capacity reservoir has reached 
44.3 million gallons. Lanie Jones and Frank Messina 
</P>
</TEXT>
